{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6ac09cb-f657-42f8-a162-904e93338185","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no special setup needed.\n\n**Look for `.ips` crash logs here:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nFind your app's report:\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | grep <YourAppName>\n```\n\nThe `.ips` file contains the native backtrace, exception type, faulting thread, and register state.\n\n**For a core dump** (not generated by default on macOS):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n# Re-run your app — core file appears in /cores/\n```\n\n**Tip:** If you have the `.ips` file and need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames, the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill can help with that.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"046e4640-5d6b-4b99-b149-7829739cf074","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates a `.ips` crash report in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes). These are the Apple crash logs.\n\nFor NativeAOT specifically, `createdump` is not available (it's a CoreCLR tool). The options are:\n\n\n- **macOS crash reports (.ips files)**: Automatically generated by ReportCrash in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **Core dumps**: macOS disables core dumps by default, but you can enable them with `ulimit -c unlimited` and possibly `sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1`\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":484,"requestId":"6406:C174F:14F1DC1:186F1C0:69EC1988"},"id":"92a1534d-4e92-4bcd-99a4-e986a0f76382","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:32:04.659Z","parentId":"f79fc6e3-0b99-4679-aa3d-78040bde9576"}
